bloodshed of pointy eared half breeds, and blue skinned devils, he saw war, and humans fighting next to Shanks, helping them rather than ignoring them,  he saw the snows of Halas, deep and pure again, he saw the crowning of a human warrior covered in blood of his enemies, he saw the birth of an ogre with hatred in his eyes, he saw Shanks drinking ale, singing songs, and clarity in their eyes he had never known.<br>
he saw the future. . .</font><P><P><i></i></TD></TR><TR BGCOLOR=#CCCCCC><TD NOWRAP width=20% valign=top align=left><B><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=2>Parin</FONT></B><BR><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1>Unregistered User</FONT><BR><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1>(</FONT><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1 COLOR=#FF0000>5/31/00</FONT> <FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1 COLOR=#FF0000>12:59:55 pm</FONT><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1>)<BR></FONT></TD><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT><B><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Verdana,Arial">The cold.....</font></B><HR><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Verdana,Arial">I watched none to comfortably from my frozen shadowed perch.  She sat at a large wooden desk (large by his standards) and wrote at length.  He had not dared to approach close enough to see the words she spilled onto the parchment, that would be.....unwise.<br>
<br>
I had followed her through this bleak and desolate land, my interest peaked by rumors of skilled folk in this land of oafs...a rumor I doubted I would find any truth in, and yet I had to know.<br>
<br>
The trip was long, and I took it with great caution.  This &quot;lady&quot; had moves on her, that is a fact.  I had seen her fight, and for her size I must admit to myself; she is good.<br>
<br>
A few of her countrymen fell to my blade, they having accidentally stumbled upon my places of hiding...thier last mistake to be sure. A strong people out of need; for the weak could not survive this clime for long, the fights still had not even been close.<br>
<br>
She had met with what I believe to be members of her Clan, the fact that she could even write went against all I had heard of the Barbarians....investigation for pleasure had turned into a mission of great import to me.  Know thy enemy my father had always said, alas; he proved to be one of them...I shall almost miss him.<br>
<br>
I do not know what those words were that she scribed, but she did so for hours; perhaps battle plans, perhaps personal letters, perhaps a list for shopping.  The thought of passing the guards, entering the building, stealing the note, and returning through all of that raced in my mind...I let them race to thier hearts content...they would not be acted upon.<br>
<br>
Many men and women had entered where she sat now, not directly to her but definitely the same building.  All were armed, and a good portion chose the weapons I my self had or desired....this did not look like a good thing.<br>
<br>
I sat there for hours before it dawned on me that this Barbarian had captured my eye....&quot;Bah&quot; I almost actually uttered...she was weak!!  Simple to think, not so easy to believe.  I have always had a fondness for strength, especially in women; and THIS woman was both strong and oddly, facinatingly....beautiful?<br>
<br>
Bah!! I actually muttered it under my breath (a mistake to be sure, but the sounds of drunken Barbarians likely drowned out my faux pas).  I relaxed and continued to watch.<br>
<br>
Her hand moved over the paper in an odd fashion.  I puzzled this in my mind until I realized she had sent signal to her Clan.  I had been discovered...this both thrilled and disappointed me.  The signal was smooth but I had at least noticed it, it was a tip off that there were hunters coming for me. The game was afoot and I knew from the hushed tones in the building that they came in number, a good clue to have.  The slight movement out of the corner of my eye was my next clue that I had been discovered....not to mention the pain from the knife lodged in my leg.  <br>
<br>
Sure I had not been spotted directly, but that he/she who had thrown the weapon had done so at the shape he saw and not the &quot;person&quot;; I calculated my choices.  Made my decision, quaffed a potion and arrived promptly in Neriak.<br>
<br>
The bartender made as if to comment but my fist silenced him, he brought me an ale and a cloth.<br>
<br>
As I tended my minor wound, I pondered this Barbarian lady, her Clan, her homeland.  It wasn't so much a fear that I felt, nor like a dread.  With a sigh and a swig of ale I came abruptly to a conclusion.  I almost smiled as the thought struck me...another worthy adversary in Norrath........how grand life is!  A shame they won't be allowed to prosper..........<br>
<br>
<br>
Parin<br>
<br>
</font><P><P><i></i></TD></TR><TR BGCOLOR=#a8a8a8><TD NOWRAP width=20% valign=top align=left><B><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=2><A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/ufricka.showPublicProfile>Fricka</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/globalBlack.gif BORDER=0 HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10></FONT></B><BR><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1>Administrator</FONT><BR><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1>(</FONT><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1 COLOR=#FF0000>6/1/00</FONT> <FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1 COLOR=#FF0000>10:34:57 am</FONT><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1>)<BR></FONT></TD><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT><B><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Verdana,Arial">Re: Roleplay -- Allies?</font></B><HR><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Verdana,Arial">Fricka felt the change in the air, she was not blessed in the Shamanic arts as others in the Horde were, but she knew when she was being watched.  Most days she would have given the signal immediately but she felt a strange undercurrent from the gaze presently upon her.  What was it?  She felt the intensity of a predator in the gaze, she was used to that, but something else ... perhaps puzzlement?  She continued writing but covertly secured the hairpin dagger in her left hand as she brushed her hair from her face.<br>
<br>
Still no movement from the watcher.  She gave the signal and waited.<br>
<br>
-----<br>
<br>
It was one of the younger Shanks who came in to report.  He did not salute and stood easy, there was usually little formality in the Horde. “The squad thinks it was a male dark elf most likely from the looks of the prints in the snow ... but I’m afraid I threw too early, he vanished without a trace -- might be a magick user”  The Shank lowered his eyes at admitting the last but raised them up again, “I drew blood though.”<br>
<br>
