<br>
Now to find Thorac lest next time my folly costs Fricka her life.</font><P><P><i></i></TD></TR><TR BGCOLOR=#a8a8a8><TD NOWRAP width=20% valign=top align=left><B><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=2><A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/btheshanks.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=thorac>Thorac</A></FONT></B><BR><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1>Local user</FONT><BR><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1>(</FONT><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1 COLOR=#FF0000>6/6/00</FONT> <FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1 COLOR=#FF0000>7:13:28 am</FONT><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1>)<BR></FONT></TD><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT><B><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Verdana,Arial">Re: Allies</font></B><HR><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Verdana,Arial">Pain...darkness...pain...something?<br>
<br>
As the pain began to subside, he opened his eyes - and the pain flared fresh and harsh!<br>
<br>
&quot;Easy my son, you've had a trying time.&quot; said a calm, fatherly voice.<br>
<br>
He answered &quot;Where..how..what..?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;You were brought in here more dead than alive, naked and wet.  Someone mentioned fishing you out of the River of Death in the rottin realm under Guk.  Foolish lad, whatever were you doing there?  Even if not for the ancient undead that infest the place, the whole area swarms with Trolls, Ogres and worse!  You're lucky it were another Northman that found you, otherwise the savages that dwell there might well be feasting on your eyes!  Too bad about your gear, you were brought in as I see you now - but at least you'll live.&quot;<br>
<br>
He remembered:  Following leads, reading maps, deciphering ramblings and writings.  He was searching for the artifact that would make him supreme as a scout and spy - a mask, a magical mask that would allow him to see in the dark and even assume the form of a foul Tier'Dal to better infiltrate enemy strongholds.  <br>
<br>
He'd failed.  All his gear was safe.  The 'Merchants' guild of Freeport had actually placed in the city's own vaults for safekeeping.  He'd made the journey South across the desert and through the swamps carrying just food and water enough for the trip.  He's looted a corpse in Innothule and picked up an old warhammer that he carried as though a travelling shaman.<br>
<br>
Once he's snaked his way to the bottom of old Guk, he recognized the passage from its description in an old text.  From here, he knew the way!  He'd carefully memorized the map.  He even overheard on of the Tier'Dal in the corridor describing the creature said to possess the mask!  If his ears were to be believed, this was a huge stroke of luck!  The guardian slain and the mask safe in its hiding place!<br>
<br>
He set off at the best speed he could manage and still remain safe from prying eyes.  Past Ogres, Trolls, Tier'Dal and a couple of undead frog-like creatures that resembled the residents above - but much more sinister and deadly.  He reached the end of the first hallway, took a deep breath and slipped into the foul, icy water to make the next leg of the journey - this was a shortcut detailed in one rambling account..<br>
<br>
He made it easily through the dark tunnel and crawled out of the water in what looked like an ancient bedroom.  There were several more of the undead frog creatures but he'd snuck past many already and these should present no more problems than the others.  He came to a fork and took the right and darker of the 2.  As he reach the point where they merged back together, he saw 3 huge rotting bats flying in the cavern.  They could sense him if he got too close - the left passage would take him farther from them, so he backtracked to the junction.<br>
<br>
Suddenly a howl went up and an ancient Lord of the foul place smashed stone from the walls inches from his head!  He'd been found out!  Without hesitation he leaped over the foul creature and dove headlong across the room for the relative safety of the stream - counting on the centuries having slowed his attacker enough to allow him escape.<br>
<br>
Whatever foul magicks kept the creature from turning to dust had also kept its speed and reflexes alive as well - this time the gleaming mace caught him in mid-air the way a child club catches the stone to send it far into the air!  He didn't even remember hitting the icy water - already unconscious.<br>
<br>
HE had failed.  But he knew what must be done.  Obviously, he wasn't smart enough to walk away given the chance to do so.  He would skulk about in the shadows and wait for a hardy group to clear that first area of undeath - perhaps even the vile bats as well and slip deeper into the temple to the hiding place of his treasure.<br>
<br>
Was this what they called obsession?<br>
<br>
